**Paragraph 5:**
• The story progresses with Pua-li'i (child/descendant of a chief/chiefly line) going out to fish, leaving Nā-maka-o-ka-pāo'o (the eyes of the pāo'o fish) and seventeen other children at his sweet potato patch; 
– The number seventeen (umi kumamāhiku: ten and seven) may have cultural or esoteric significance. In some Hawaiian stories, specific numbers hold symbolic meaning, so it's possible that seventeen represents a particular concept or theme;
• Nā-maka-o-ka-pāo'o is described as being very small in stature, at two and a half feet tall, and still having an unhealed navel, indicating he is likely still a toddler or very young child. This emphasizes his youth and vulnerability;
• Upon reaching the sweet potato patch, Nā-maka-o-ka-pāo'o instructs the other children to completely destroy the patch by pulling out both the tubers and the leaves, leaving nothing to regrow. This act can be seen as destructive and may symbolize a disruption or challenge to the existing order or practices, possibly related to the 'Ai Kapu era's emphasis on agriculture and food production;
– The name Nā-maka-o-ka-pāo'o, with 'Nā-maka' (the eyes) potentially symbolizing insight, understanding, or a connection to the maka (sweet potato vine cuttings used for replanting), and 'pāo'o' (a poetic or metaphorical reference to 'po'o', the head), may be allegorically linked to the act of destroying the sweet potato patch. The 'eyes' could represent the potential for regrowth or the 'seed' for future crops, while 'pāo'o'/'po'o' might signify the source or origin;
• The other children are afraid to follow Nā-maka-o-ka-pāo'o's instructions, choosing instead to gently handle the sweet potatoes without pulling out the tubers. This hesitation may indicate a recognition of the wrongdoing or a fear of the consequences of such an action, possibly reflecting the cultural values of responsibility and stewardship associated with agricultural practices during the 'Ai Kapu era;
• The act of destroying the sweet potato patch and the reaction of the other children could be seen as a narrative device to explore themes related to obedience, authority, and the consequences of one's actions within the context of Hawaiian cultural practices and traditions.
